The only non-terminals that can directly produce the terminals in the string are

t112 → NT7  
t28  → NT81  
t58  → NT9  
t43  → NT72, NT97  
t105 → NT99  
t149 → NT4  
t90  → NT69, NT89  

So the length-1 CYK sets for the 7 positions are  

1:{NT7}  2:{NT81}  3:{NT9}  4:{NT72,NT97}  5:{NT99}  6:{NT4}  7:{NT69,NT89}

To build any larger substring, a binary rule A → B C must match some adjacent pair of these sets.

Checking every adjacent pair:

(1,2): NT7 NT81 – no rule A→NT7 NT81  
(2,3): NT81 NT9 – no rule  
(3,4): NT9 NT72 or NT9 NT97 – no rule with NT9 followed by NT72/NT97  
(4,5): NT72 NT99 or NT97 NT99 – no rule  
(5,6): NT99 NT4 – no rule  
(6,7): NT4 NT69 or NT4 NT89 – no rule

Since no contiguous pair of tokens can be combined, no substring of length 2 can be generated. Without a length-2 constituent, no larger constituent (and therefore no complete length-7 parse) can be formed, because the grammar has no ε-productions or unary (A→B) productions.

Consequently the start symbol S cannot derive the given 7-token string.

No

To reach the start symbol S, one of the two start rules must be used:

1. S → NT0 NT13
2. S → NT62 NT39

Rule 2 forces the very first token of the derived string to be either ‘t35’ or ‘t151’, because NT62 can only produce those two terminals.  
Our target string starts with ‘t73’, so rule 2 is impossible.

Rule 1 expands to

S → NT0 NT13  
  NT0 → NT88 NT22  
  NT13 → NT21 NT3

So any string generated via rule 1 has the form  

(tokens from NT88)  (tokens from NT22)  (tokens from NT21)  (tokens from NT3).

Focus on NT21.  The grammar contains only one production for NT21:

NT21 → NT85 NT83

and NT85, in turn, has only

NT85 → NT4 NT91

with NT4 being strictly terminal:

NT4 → 't149' | 't57'

Therefore every string that contains an NT21 segment must contain at least one occurrence of either ‘t149’ or ‘t57’.  
The target string

t73 t43 t43 t22 t44 t154 t46 t118 t44 t58 t10 t10 t43

contains neither ‘t149’ nor ‘t57’.  Consequently, no derivation can create this string using the only possible start rule.

Hence the given grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

The only non-terminal in the grammar that can yield the terminal symbol ‘t28’ is NT81, via the rule

    NT81 -> 't28'

To have ‘t28’ as the very first symbol of the derived string, the start symbol S must ultimately begin its derivation with NT81.

The grammar offers exactly two rules for S:

    S -> NT0 NT13
    S -> NT62 NT39

1.  S → NT62 NT39    
    NT62 has only terminal rules  

        NT62 -> 't35' | 't151'

    so any string derived through this rule must start with either t35 or t151, never with t28. Hence this alternative cannot produce the given string.

2.  S → NT0 NT13, where NT0 → NT88 NT22.  
    Therefore the leftmost symbol of any string derived from S through this route is determined by NT88.

    NT88 has only the following possibilities:

        NT88 -> NT98 NT111
        NT88 -> NT94 NT51
        NT88 -> NT46 NT76

    Examining each left-hand non-terminal:

        NT98 can begin with 't76' or with NT83 (which begins with 't70');  
        NT94 begins with NT110 (either 't154' or 't40');  
        NT46 can begin with 't58', 't5', 't149', 't131', or 't125'.

    None of these options can yield ‘t28’ as their first terminal; NT81 never occurs in the leftmost position of any expansion of NT88.

Consequently, no derivation from the start symbol S can produce a string whose first token is t28, while the string we are asked to recognise does begin with t28. Therefore the given string is not generated by the grammar.
